04089nam a22006855i 9780691237589DE-B159720220110023848.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220110t20221998nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912375897 a10.1515/97806912375892doi  a(DE-B1597)602093  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHB135b.A555 1998eb 7aBUS0690002bisacsh04a330/.01/1852221 aAlbin, Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBarriers and Bounds to Rationality :bEssays on Economic Complexity and Dynamics in Interactive Systems /cPeter Albin; ed. by Duncan K. Foley. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©1998  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b36 line illus. 23 halftones 12 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPrinceton Studies in Complexity ;v400 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPeter Albin is known for his seminal work in applying the concepts of adaptive dynamical systems, first developed by biologists and physicists, to the study of economic systems. This book is a collection of his pathbreaking articles on the application of cellular automata and complexity theory to economic problems. Duncan Foley provides a thoughtful introduction in which he reviews the disparate analytical sources of Albin's work in the theories of nonlinear dynamical systems, economic dynamics, cellular automata, linguistic and computational complexity, and bounded rationality. Albin has analyzed economic systems as interactions of highly complex components (i.e., intelligent human beings). He uses the theories of generative linguistics and cellular automata to establish that the complexity level of economic systems is, in principle at least, that of a Turing machine or general-purpose computer, establishing that classic economic approaches to the problems of household and firm choice, macroeconomic prediction, and policy evaluation may give rise to undecidable propositions and uncomputable functions. He develops simple models of dynamic economic interaction based on cellular automata which illustrate the inherent complexity of economic interactions and the resulting challenge they pose to traditional theories of rational economic behavior. These models explore the dynamics of the business cycle, decentralized market trading, and the emergence of cooperation in a novel local-interaction version of the repeated prisoners' dilemma game. Albin's work provides a unique and important perspective on economic systems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 10. Jan 2022) 0aComputational complexity. 0aEconomics, Mathematical. 0aStatics and dynamics (Social sciences). 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / General.2bisacsh1 aFoley, Duncan K., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691237589423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691237589/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK